  "title": "Proportionality and Direct Variation Prep Activities",
  "body": " Proportionality and Direct Variation Prep Activities   Two varying quantities and have a proportional relationship when the ratio between the quantities is constant. That is, and have a proportional relationship when always has the same value. We call the constant of proportionality.      Peyton is using an app to track data about their recent activity. The tables below show time, , (measured in minutes) and distance, from their starting location (measured in miles) data from three of Peyton's recent activity sessions.    Walk        5  0.25    10  0.5    15  0.75    20  1.0    25  1.25      Hike        10  0.5    20  0.75    30  1.0    40  1.5    50  1.75      Bike Ride        10  2.5    20  5.0    30  7.5    40  10.0    50  12.5         Find for each row in the Walk table. Use your results to determine whether Peyton's time and distance on their walk have a proportional relationship.      Find for each row in the Hike table. Use your results to determine whether Peyton's time and distance on their hike have a proportional relationship.      Find for each row in the Bike Ride table. Use your results to determine whether Peyton's time and distance on their bike ride have a proportional relationship.      What is the constant of proportionality for each of the activities in which Peyton's time and distance had a proportional relationship?      Interpret the constant of proportionality in context. That is, what does it tell us about the relationship between Peyton's time and distance?       When two quantities have a proportional relationship, it is often useful to rewrite the equation as . We sometimes say that  varies directly with respect to .     Use your work from to write an equation that shows that Peyton's distance varies directly with respect to time for one of their activities.      Use your equation to predict Peyton's distance after 65 minutes of activity.      Use your equation to predict how long it would take Peyton to go 3.0 miles.       In this unit, we will need to be able to solve equations of the form , where the values of , , and are known.    Divide by sides by .    When is a positive whole number, take the n-th root of both sides.    Here is an example:   Solving an equation with an unknown base and a known power.         Divide by sides by 3, and compute     Take the 3rd root, , of both sides     Calculate     The TI-30XIIS calculator can calculate the th root using 2nd + ^. To calculate , for example, press 3, then 2nd, then ^, then 8, then =. We will study roots more carefully in a few lessons, but you will need to be able to use them to solve equations in the next class period.     Use roots to find a solution to each of the following equations:                           In previous math classes, you may have learned that when the power is even, like in , then there are two solutions. You found one of them above. What's the other solution?      You'll need to be able to do the following things for this lesson. Rate how confident you are on a scale of 1 - 5 (1 = not confident and 5 = very confident).     Skill or Concept: I can …  Rating from 1 to 5    Determine whether two quantities have a proportional relationship.     Find the constant of proportionality for two quantities with a proportional relationship from a data table.     Write an equation that shows a quantity varies directly with respect to another quantity .     Use roots to solve an equation of the form .       "
