  "title": "Power Model Trends Prep Activities",
  "body": " Power Model Trends Prep Activities    The table below shows the average price per pound ($\/lb) of 100% beef ground chuck in the US in May    Average Price Per Pound ($\/lb) of Ground Chuck in the US    Year  Price Per Pound    2006  2.508    2011  3.277    2016  3.902    2021  4.495    2026  6.718        Sketch a graph showing this data. (Start by setting up axes! Do you need to include any negatives?)      Find a formula for a linear model for this data. (If you're stuck, start by finding an average rate of change to use as your slope estimate. Then, ask yourself: what else do I need to finish this model?)      Use your model to estimate the average cost of ground chuck in 2010.      The actual average cost in 2010 was $2.921\/lb. How well did your model do?      Use your model to estimate when the average cost of ground chuck was $5\/lb.      The actual average cost in 2022 was $4.894, in 2023 was $4.953, and in 2024 was $5.331. How well did you model do?       Although a linear model is a reasonable fit for the ground chuck cost data, an exponential model is better. Let's review finding and using exponential models.     First, we find the of the cost only. Use your calculator to fill in these values in the table below.   Average Price Per Pound ($\/lb) of Ground Chuck in the US with Log($\/lb)    Year  Price Per Pound  Log($\/lb)    2006  2.508     2011  3.277     2016  3.902     2021  4.495     2026  6.718          Sketch a new graph that shows the years on the horizontal axis, and Log($\/lb) on the vertical axis. This type of graph is sometimes called a semi-log graph , since one of the axes is the log of the data.      Find a linear model for Log($\/lb) with respect to year. (If you're stuck, ask yourself: what information do I need in order to build a linear model?)      Use your linear model for Log($\/lb) to estimate . Then, raise 10 to the power of your answer in order to get an estimate for the cost in 2010. How did this model do?      In order to use this model to estimate when the cost of ground chuck was $5\/lb, start by finding . Then, plug into the appropriate place in your model formula and use algebra to estimate the year. How did the model do on this estimate?      In order to use this model to estimate the cost in a given year, we always have to raise 10 to the power of the output of our model. Sometimes, it's convenient to rewrite the model in exponential form, as   where is the cost in $\/lb and your linear model for Log($\/lb). Write your model in this format.      You'll need to be able to do the following things for this lesson. Rate how confident you are on a scale of 1 - 5 (1 = not confident and 5 = very confident).     Skill or Concept: I can …  Rating from 1 to 5    Find a linear model for a data set that is only approximately linear.     Use a calculator to find of a column of data.     Undo a by raising 10 to the power of a number.       "
